ChatGPT said:
Hereâ€™s how to create the required Terraform directory structure and configuration files in Cloud Shell. This setup will use the region, zone, and project_id variables throughout, and define a Terraform block with the Google provider.

âœ… Step 1: Create Directory Structure
Run this in Cloud Shell:

mkdir -p terraform-project/modules/instances
mkdir -p terraform-project/modules/storage
cd terraform-project
touch main.tf variables.tf
touch modules/instances/{instances.tf,outputs.tf,variables.tf}
touch modules/storage/{storage.tf,outputs.tf,variables.tf}

âœ… Step 2: Root variables.tf
variable "project_id" {
type = string
default = "your-google-cloud-project-id"
}

variable "region" {
type = string
default = "us-central1"
}

variable "zone" {
type = string
default = "us-central1-c"
}
Replace "your-google-cloud-project-id" with your actual project ID.

âœ… Root main.tf
terraform {
required_providers {
google = {
source = "hashicorp/google"
version = "~> 4.0"
}
}

required_version = ">= 1.3.0"
}

provider "google" {
project = var.project_id
region = var.region
zone = var.zone
}
âœ… modules/instances/variables.tf
variable "project_id" {
type = string
default = "your-google-cloud-project-id"
}

variable "region" {
type = string
default = "us-central1"
}

variable "zone" {
type = string
default = "us-central1-c"
}
âœ… modules/storage/variables.tf
variable "project_id" {
type = string
default = "your-google-cloud-project-id"
}

variable "region" {
type = string
default = "us-central1"
}

variable "zone" {
type = string
default = "us-central1-c"
}
Once this setup is complete, you can begin defining your actual resources in instances.tf and storage.tf, using the variables like so:

