ChatGPT said:
Hereâ€™s a step-by-step guide to meet your requirements using the Terraform Registry VPC module:

âœ… Step 1: Use the VPC Module (v6.0.0)
In your main.tf, add the following block:

module "tf_vpc" {
source = "terraform-google-modules/network/google"
version = "6.0.0"

project_id = var.project_id
network_name = "tf-vpc-448496"
routing_mode = "GLOBAL"

subnets = [
{
subnet_name = "subnet-01"
subnet_ip = "10.10.10.0/24"
subnet_region = "us-central1"
},
{
subnet_name = "subnet-02"
subnet_ip = "10.10.20.0/24"
subnet_region = "us-central1"
}
]
}
âœ… Step 2: Initialize & Apply
terraform init
terraform apply -auto-approve
This will create the VPC and both subnets using the specified module and IP ranges.

âœ… Step 3: Update instances.tf to Use New Subnets
In modules/instances/instances.tf, update the two instances like so:

resource "google_compute_instance" "tf_instance_1" {
name = "tf-instance-1"
machine_type = "e2-medium"
zone = var.zone
project = var.project_id

boot_disk {
initialize_params {
image = "debian-cloud/debian-11"
}
}

network_interface {
network = "tf-vpc-448496"
subnetwork = "subnet-01"
access_config {}
}

metadata_startup_script = <<-EOT
#!/bin/bash
EOT

allow_stopping_for_update = true
}

resource "google_compute_instance" "tf_instance_2" {
name = "tf-instance-2"
machine_type = "e2-medium"
zone = var.zone
project = var.project_id

boot_disk {
initialize_params {
image = "debian-cloud/debian-11"
}
}

network_interface {
network = "tf-vpc-448496"
subnetwork = "subnet-02"
access_config {}
}

metadata_startup_script = <<-EOT
#!/bin/bash
EOT

allow_stopping_for_update = true
}
âœ… Final Step: Re-Apply
After updating instances.tf, run:

terraform apply -auto-approve
This will update the network interface on both instances to connect them to the correct subnets.

